<H3 class=3Dentry-title><A=20
title=3D'Permanent Link to "What is OAI and why should you&nbsp;care?"'=20
href=3D"http://za3038.wordpress.com/2008/05/06/what-is-oai-and-why-should=
-you-care/"=20
rel=3Dbookmark>What is OAI and why should you&nbsp;care?</A></H3><SMALL=20
class=3Dentry-meta><SPAN class=3Dchronodata>Published <ABBR =
class=3Dpublished=20
title=3D2008-05-06T15:57:05+0000>May 6, 2008</ABBR> </SPAN><SPAN=20
class=3Dentry-category><A title=3D"View all posts in Uncategorized"=20
href=3D"http://za3038.wordpress.com/category/uncategorized/"=20
rel=3D"category tag">Uncategorized</A></SPAN> <BR>Tags: <A=20
href=3D"http://wordpress.com/tag/oai/" rel=3Dtag>oai</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://wordpress.com/tag/open-archives-initiative/" =
rel=3Dtag>Open Archives=20
Initiative</A><BR></SMALL><!-- .entry-meta --></DIV><!-- .entry-head -->
<DIV class=3Dentry-content>
<DIV class=3Dsnap_preview>
<P>The Open Archives Initiative, commonly abbreviated as OAI, is a =
=E2=80=9Cbody that=20
promotes standards in archiving which allow systems to operate =
successfully=20
together and exchange information.=E2=80=9D (Dictionary of Information =
and Library=20
Management) Founded by Michael Nelson, Carl Lagoze, and Herbert Van de =
Sompel,=20
the OAI first launched in October of 1999. The Initiative=E2=80=99s =
funding comes from=20
the Andrew W. Mellon Foundation, the Coalition for Networked =
Information,=20
Digital Library Federation, Microsoft Corporation, and the National =
Science=20
Foundation. (Reitz, Open Archives Initiative) Since its inception, the=20
Initiative has been linked conceptually to the idea of <A=20
href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_o.cfm#openaccess">open access</A> in =
scholarly=20
publishing and the creation of institutional repositories. For this =
reason it=20
has garnered considerable support from information and library science=20
professionals. However, increasingly effective, mainstream alternatives =
to the=20
OAI=E2=80=99s framework have resulted in published authors not =
participating in the=20
Initiative. As well, vendors may be dissuaded from participating in OAI=20
repositories due to digital copyright concerns.</P>
<P>Although the above definition for OAI is good for a general =
understanding of=20
the Initiative, it does not provide a comprehensive understanding of the =
topic.=20
At its core, the OAI promotes interoperability between different systems =
by=20
supplying a rigorous set of standards that facilitate the sharing of =
digital=20
information. While the name OAI suggests the idea of a permanent =
repository for=20
digital or digitized media, the word =E2=80=9Carchive=E2=80=9D is in =
fact used as a synonym for=20
=E2=80=9C<A =
href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_e.cfm#eprint">e-prints</A>=E2=80=9D. =
(Reitz) The two=20
definitions of archive should not be confused, because while the former =
is=20
focused on artifacts and artifactual value, the latter=E2=80=99s goal is =
to increase=20
scholarly communication by creating easier digital access to research. =
Although=20
the two are not mutually exclusive, this distinction is vital to =
properly=20
understanding the OAI.</P>
<P>The OAI=E2=80=99s main vehicle for increasing scholarly communication =
is OAI-PMH, or=20
the Open Archives Initiative Protocol for Metadata Harvesting. (<A=20
href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_m.cfm#metadata">Metadata</A> is, at =
its most=20
basic, information about information.) Metadata harvesters locate and =
aggregate=20
metadata from different data sets. While this at first may seem =
confusing, there=20
are many easy-to-understand examples. If I wanted to integrate <A=20
href=3D"http://www.lib.umich.edu/mdp/">MBooks</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://books.google.com/">Google Books</A>, and CMU=E2=80=99s <A =

href=3D"http://www.ulib.org/">Million Book Project</A> into my own =
catalogue, all=20
I would have to do is =E2=80=9Cpoint=E2=80=9D my metadata harvester at =
their repositories to=20
gather the information. With the OAI, <A=20
href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_d.cfm#dublincore">Dublin Core</A> is =
usually=20
used as the scheme for metadata. Afterward, when searching my <A=20
href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_o.cfm#opac">OPAC</A>, users would be =
able to=20
locate the metadata =E2=80=93 in record form =E2=80=93 within my =
catalogue and be linked to the=20
content at the original repository=E2=80=99s site. This is impressive =
not only because=20
it can widely diversify an institution=E2=80=99s collection, but also =
because none of=20
the files (besides metadata) have to be stored locally. The largest OAI=20
catalogue is <A href=3D"http://www.oaister.org/">OAIster</A>, which =
provides=20
access to approximately 15 =C2=BD million records. (University of =
Michigan) The=20
search engine indexes material from over 900 contributors. (University =
of=20
Michigan)</P>
<P>I am skeptical, however, of OAI-PMH. First of all, acquiring metadata =
is not=20
as simple as pointing your harvester at an information source. =
Permission must=20
be asked and granted, and there is no guarantee that more contemporary =
and=20
valuable information will come without a fee. The majority of the works =
in the=20
digital repositories listed above are either in the public domain or =
have been=20
digitized as =E2=80=9C<A =
href=3D"http://www.copyright.gov/orphan/">orphan works</A>=E2=80=9D. =
They=20
may lack currency, not reflect advances in science and society, and not=20
represent a holistic collection of knowledge. Also, scholarly material,=20
especially in the hard sciences and articles being prepared for =
publishing,may=20
not be as likely to be freely available.</P>
<P>A second concern hinges on digital preservation and continual access. =
If=20
institutions are simply collecting metadata about e-prints and other =
information=20
resources, this means that there may only be one institution with an =
actual=20
electronic copy. If that copy and its backups were lost, access to the =
full text=20
=E2=80=93 one of the main concerns of the OAI =E2=80=93 would be =
undermined. Author <A=20
href=3D"http://cyber.law.harvard.edu/people/dweinberger">David =
Weinberger</A>=20
advocates an item being in more than one place at the same time in <A=20
href=3D"http://www.worldcat.org/oclc/122291427"><EM>Everything is=20
Miscellaneous</EM></A> through the use of metadata; however, it may make =
more=20
sense for an item to be in more than one place literally, through =
duplicate=20
electronic copies. A related concern is that the status of currently =
free=20
full-text materials owned by private and/or corporate institutions may =
change.=20
As a result, access to such materials would disappear overnight. This is =

significant because most high-profile mass-digitization projects are =
being=20
spearheaded by companies such as Google, rather than consortia of =
libraries,=20
archives, and academic institutions. A possible solution to these =
problems is=20
the <A href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_l.cfm#lockss">LOCKSS</A> =
(=E2=80=9CLots of Copies=20
Keeps Stuff Safe=E2=80=9D) project. Like the name implies, redundant =
(and decentralized)=20
storing of information could allow for more permanent and reliable =
access to=20
this information, something that the Open Archives Initiative inherently =

neglects by its metadata-centered design.</P>
<P>So far I have addressed predominantly digitized book collections in =
relation=20
to OAI metadata harvesting. However, the original and continued focus of =
the OAI=20
is on e-prints, or research and journal articles. As Peter Suber stated, =

=E2=80=9COAI-compliant archives are already here and already =
useful=E2=80=9D. (Suber, May 2) So=20
why then have they not challenged commercially offered databases? The =
answer is=20
that scholars must not only be convinced of the value of OAI to include =
their=20
works, but also that OAI repositories must be filled with quality =
materials that=20
exploit the benefits of the OAI standards.</P>
<P>Depositing research in an OAI compliant repository is arguably not a =
priority=20
or norm in the scholarly world. In OAIster, I searched for several of my =

instructors from library school. Of the five, only three had articles in =
the=20
catalogue. For many authors, putting a paper on their personal website =
can be=20
seen as the equivalent of depositing in a repository. Not only have they =

achieved open access, but using Google, or some future search engine =
with=20
similar functionality, will allow users worldwide to find their work. =
The=20
argument against this is that OAI=E2=80=99s use of fielded metadata =
allows for precision=20
searching. (Suber, March 2) However, relevancy algorithms and properly =
executed=20
XML effectively perform the same function as fielded searches. The =
question of=20
whether search engines or OAI catalogues are superior is a highly =
contentious=20
one, and there is little besides opinion in the scholarly literature to=20
substantiate one side over the other. Peter Suber points to the =
following=20
statements as examples of library and information science =
professionals=E2=80=99=20
unfounded preference for OAI:</P>
<BLOCKQUOTE>
  <P>=E2=80=9CBut OA-OAI archiving enhances visibility more than Google =
indexing does.=E2=80=9D=20
  [=E2=80=A6] =E2=80=9CScholars doing serious scholarly research look in =
specialized scholarly=20
  tools and resources before they look in Google.=E2=80=9D [=E2=80=A6] =
=E2=80=9CArchiving will give an=20
  eprint a permanent or persistent URL.=E2=80=9D [=E2=80=A6] =
=E2=80=9COAI-compliant searching tools=20
  refresh their indices faster than Google.=E2=80=9D (Suber, March =
2)</P></BLOCKQUOTE>
<P>These assertions are flawed for many reasons. First, they ignore the =
use of=20
e-prints by non-scholars. Second, they make broad, sweeping =
generalizations=20
about Google, scholarly research methods, and OAI searching tools; these =

statements do not hold true in all cases. For every assertion of the =
OAI=E2=80=99s=20
superiority, Suber =E2=80=93 a proponent of the OAI =E2=80=93 can find =
many convincing=20
exceptions.</P>
<P>When a persuasive argument cannot be made for one tool over the =
other, why=20
should scholars participate in an OAI compliant system? The answer is =
that a=20
service like Google does not detract from the value of OAI, that the =
systems=20
need not be mutually exclusive, and that OAI has the potential to offer =
a=20
superior search experience should mass-collaboration be achieved. =
(Suber, March=20
2) Were mass-collaboration achieved, users would have access to =
substantial,=20
cross-disciplinary databases of scholarly literature. Inappropriate =
materials=20
would be excluded, decreasing the <A=20
href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_i.cfm#infooverload">information =
overload</A> so=20
often experienced by users of search engines. This would also reduce the =

likelihood that users not versed in information literacy would utilize =
incorrect=20
or flawed information resources. While David Weinberger suggests that=20
information professionals =E2=80=9Cgive up control=E2=80=9D and =
=E2=80=9Cfilter on the way out, not on=20
the way in=E2=80=9D, the OAI intends to do the exact opposite. (105, =
102) In doing so,=20
they hope to create bastions of knowledge known not only for their =
intellectual=20
integrity, but supreme usability.</P>
<P>To enhance the value of OAI compliant repositories, Suber identified =
ten=20
goals which information professionals should work toward. They include: =
working=20
against the Ingelfinger Rule (a stipulation in contracts that prevents=20
publishing of already available research), persuading all open access =
journals=20
to participate, persuading publishers to supply metadata for their =
materials=20
regardless of whether the documents are copyrighted or not in electronic =

formats, archiving =E2=80=9Craw and semi-raw data, not just articles =
that interpret or=20
analyze data=E2=80=9D, and finally creating an open access citation =
index. (Suber, March=20
2) Other goals Suber listed have already been achieved in part, =
including making=20
=E2=80=9Cpostprint archiving [=E2=80=A6] a condition of research =
funding=E2=80=9D (now true of=20
government-funded research) and the depositing of theses and =
dissertations (true=20
of many colleges/universities). (Suber, March 2) While these measures =
would=20
predominantly ensure a steady flow of current material, I think that the =
most=20
exciting goals are those involving publishers and the creation of a =
citation=20
index. These two factors will make OAI compliant catalogues discovery =
tools=20
par-excellence by creating a massive, deep (predominantly full text) =
index of=20
serials and monographs, effectively removing the need for sloppy <A=20
href=3D"http://lu.com/odlis/odlis_f.cfm#federatedsearch">federated =
search=20
engines</A> which are inhibited by the proprietary structure of =
commercial=20
databases.</P>
<P>The Open Archives Initiative relies on standards, which Roy Tennant =
has gone=20
so far as to describe as the =E2=80=9Cengine of =
interoperability=E2=80=9D. By utilizing such=20
standards to organize information, the OAI is working to increase access =
to=20
scholarly materials. Although the system has flaws and has not yet =
gained=20
mainstream acceptance, it is clear that the potential exists for =
OAI-compliant=20
technologies to radically transform the publication of academic research =
and, as=20
a result, scholarly communication. Hopefully this transformation will =
mirror the=20
value which served has guided the Initiative over time, open access to=20
information.</P>
